<subSubSection box="[151,513,438,465]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,438,1941]" box="[151,513,438,465]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,513,438,465]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,513,438,465]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[151,311,438,465]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,311,438,465]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Lysmata rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a valid species
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="202" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,438,1941]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
Here we formally resurrect 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[458,541,475,501]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[458,541,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to valid species status, concluding it is not a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1254,1355,475,500]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1254,1355,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as previously suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[390,634,511,537]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis box="[498,553,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
based upon morphological similarity between newly collected Brazilian material and published accounts of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[554,657,547,572]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[554,657,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and genetic similarity between Brazilian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1130,1214,547,573]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1130,1214,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1271,1374,547,572]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1271,1374,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,251,583,609]" name="Thailand" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(see below). While 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[473,717,583,609]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis box="[582,637,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
provided a detailed morphological analysis of material collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[181,249,619,645]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(the type locality for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[500,585,619,645]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[500,585,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), there was no corresponding analysis of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1061,1164,619,644]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1061,1164,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from its putative native range. Importantly, their conclusions were also hindered by historical uncertainty regarding accessory branch structure of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[233,335,691,716]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[233,335,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Counter to 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruce, A. J." box="[476,644,691,717]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="569 - 610" refId="ref18575" refString="Bruce, A. J. (1990) Redescriptions of five Hong Kong carideans first described by William Stimpson, 1860. Proceedings of the second international marine biological workshop: The marine fauna and flora of Hong Kong and southern China, Hong Kong, 1986, 569 - 610." type="journal article" year="1990">Bruce’s (1990)</bibRefCitation>
redescription of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[836,938,691,716]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[836,938,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a topotypic specimen, 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
stated 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[338,438,727,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[338,438,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses a one-segmented accessory branch, similar to Brazilian material identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[241,342,763,788]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[241,342,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We posit this supposition was based on misidentified material. The present study, as well as 
<bibRefCitation author="Aguilar, R. &amp; Prakash, S. &amp; Ogburn, M. B. &amp; Lohan, K. M. P. &amp; MacDonald III, K. S. &amp; Driskell, A. C. &amp; Ahyong, S. T. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; McIlroy, S. E. &amp; Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A." pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="1" refId="ref16244" refString="Aguilar, R., Prakash, S., Ogburn, M. B., Lohan, K. M. P., MacDonald III, K. S., Driskell, A. C., Ahyong, S. T., Leray, M., McIlroy, S. E., Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A. (2022) Unresolved taxonomy can confounds invasive species identification: the Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (Decapoda: Caridea: Lysmatidae) species complex and recent introduction of Lysmata vittata sensu stricto in the western Atlantic. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 42 (1). https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jcbiol / ruab 079" type="journal article" year="2022">
Aguilar 
<emphasis box="[188,245,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2022)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruce, A. J." box="[381,532,799,825]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="569 - 610" refId="ref18575" refString="Bruce, A. J. (1990) Redescriptions of five Hong Kong carideans first described by William Stimpson, 1860. Proceedings of the second international marine biological workshop: The marine fauna and flora of Hong Kong and southern China, Hong Kong, 1986, 569 - 610." type="journal article" year="1990">Bruce (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, clearly show the 
<typeStatus box="[736,824,799,825]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">neotype</typeStatus>
/topotypic material of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1075,1177,799,824]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1075,1177,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses a uniramous accessory branch, in additional to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[529,630,835,860]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[529,630,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[696,845,835,861]" name="New Zealand" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[938,998,835,861]" name="United States of America" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">USA</collectingCountry>
. Further, the genetic analyses presented in 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[180,428,871,897]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis box="[290,347,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
were hindered by the lack of material from across the full distribution of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1255,1357,871,896]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1255,1357,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Much of the strength of 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[350,617,907,933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade’s 
<emphasis box="[479,535,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
argument was based on genetic similarity between Brazilian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1305,1388,907,933]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[1305,1388,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[151,254,943,968]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[151,254,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[323,426,943,969]" name="Thailand" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. However, we posit this 
<collectingCountry box="[704,804,943,969]" name="Thailand" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Thailand</collectingCountry>
material (also included in the present analyses) was not 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[151,253,979,1004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[151,253,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(clade LV1), but rather 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[522,605,979,1005]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[522,605,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(clade LV4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="202" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,438,1941]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
In our analyses, which included material from across the western Atlantic, the northern Indo-Pacific, and Oceania, we recovered 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[364,468,1051,1076]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[364,468,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(clade LV1) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[672,758,1051,1077]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[672,758,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(clade LV4) as strongly supported clades (
<figureCitation box="[1255,1326,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[162,1417,191,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-22@14.[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 4. Phylogenetic tree obtained from Maximum Likelihood (ML) analysis of the partial 16S rRNA gene for shrimps from the Lysmata vittata species complex, selected lysmatids, and Merguia. Numbers above or below the branches represent bootstrap values obtained from ML in the webserver W-IQ-TREE (Trifinopoulos et al. 2016; http://iqtree.cibiv.univie.ac.at/). Low node values (&lt;50) were removed from the final topology. Asterisk indicates the neotype of L. vittata. Vertical bars represent dissimilar taxonomic units suggested by ASAP. Numbers below vertical bars indicate the number of species identified by ASAP (27) and ASAP-score (2.0) in the corresponding partition." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621237/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Genetic differences (
<emphasis box="[292,306,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">p</emphasis>
-distances) between these two clades were considerable (
<geoCoordinate box="[943,1007,1087,1114]" degrees="0.168" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" precision="55" value="0.168">0.168</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1007,1087,1087,1114]" degrees="0.194" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" precision="55" value="-0.194">–0.194</geoCoordinate>
) and greater than several interspecific cross-clade comparisons within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Risso" authorityYear="1816" box="[605,699,1123,1148]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[605,699,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Lysmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, e.g., 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1816" box="[768,926,1123,1149]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seticaudata">
<emphasis box="[768,926,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. seticaudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bruce" authorityYear="1983" box="[934,1057,1123,1149]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="debelius">
<emphasis box="[934,1057,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. debelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(0.139) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wicksten" authorityYear="2000" box="[1200,1406,1123,1148]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentopunctata">
<emphasis box="[1200,1406,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L argentopunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rhyne &amp; Lin" authorityYear="2006" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boggessi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. boggessi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(0.157). Our genetic analyses are supported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Aguilar, R. &amp; Prakash, S. &amp; Ogburn, M. B. &amp; Lohan, K. M. P. &amp; MacDonald III, K. S. &amp; Driskell, A. C. &amp; Ahyong, S. T. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; McIlroy, S. E. &amp; Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A." box="[796,1033,1159,1185]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="1" refId="ref16244" refString="Aguilar, R., Prakash, S., Ogburn, M. B., Lohan, K. M. P., MacDonald III, K. S., Driskell, A. C., Ahyong, S. T., Leray, M., McIlroy, S. E., Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A. (2022) Unresolved taxonomy can confounds invasive species identification: the Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (Decapoda: Caridea: Lysmatidae) species complex and recent introduction of Lysmata vittata sensu stricto in the western Atlantic. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 42 (1). https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jcbiol / ruab 079" type="journal article" year="2022">
Aguilar 
<emphasis box="[890,947,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2022)
</bibRefCitation>
, which recovered 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1241,1344,1159,1184]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1241,1344,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and “ 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">L. vittata</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[232,285,1195,1221]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">rauli</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
” from 
<collectingCountry box="[367,435,1195,1221]" name="Brazil" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Brazil</collectingCountry>
in widely divergent and strongly supported clades and delineated both clades as putative species based on ABGD analysis. Given the morphologic uncertainty surrounding 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1089,1192,1231,1256]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1089,1192,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and lack of available data at that time, 
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." box="[347,615,1267,1293]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade’s 
<emphasis box="[476,533,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
conclusions were not unreasonable and further highlights the urgency of solving the longstanding taxonomic ambiguity of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[710,811,1303,1328]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[710,811,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,438,1941]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
In addition to accessory branch structure, there are other important morphological differences which support the recognition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[355,438,1375,1401]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[355,438,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species. The number of meral and carpal segments of the second pereopod (P2) vary widely across 
<taxonomicName box="[370,553,1411,1437]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis box="[370,464,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Lysmata</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
and can be useful characteristic in delimitating species (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Chace, F. A. Jr." box="[1237,1382,1411,1437]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref19012" refString="Chace, F. A. Jr. (1997) The caridean shrimps (Crustacea: Decapoda) of the Albatross Philippine Expedition, 1907 - 1910, Part 7: Families Atyidae, Eugonatonotidae, Rhynchocinetidae, Bathypalaemonellidae, Processidae, and Hippolytidae. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 587, 1 - 106. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / 0198 - 0254 (86) 91227 - 6" type="journal article" year="1997">Chace, 1997</bibRefCitation>
). On average, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[253,337,1447,1473]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[253,337,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had fewer carpal (16.75 vs. 20.79) and meral (7.36 vs. 10.32) second pereopod segments in comparison to 
<emphasis box="[269,378,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[269,374,1483,1508]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">L. vittata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In our PCA and DFA, both aforementioned characters had high loading factors (table 3) in the first principal component, which explained nearly a third of the total variance. Although rostrum length is variable and should be treated with caution, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[554,638,1555,1581]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[554,638,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to have a slightly shorter rostrum, reaching the midpoint of the second article of antennular peduncle, as opposed to the distal margin of the same article in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1187,1289,1591,1616]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1187,1289,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Soledade, G. O. &amp; Baeza, J. A. &amp; Boehs, G. &amp; Simoes, S. M. &amp; Santos, P. S. &amp; Da Costa, R. C. &amp; Almeida, A. O. &amp; Souza Santos, P. &amp; Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O." pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="66 - 77" refId="ref23416" refString="Soledade, G. O., Baeza, J. A., Boehs, G., Simoes, S. M., Santos, P. S., Da Costa, R. C., Almeida, A. O., Souza Santos, P., Caetano da Costa, R. &amp; Almeida, A. O. (2013) A precautionary tale when describing species in a world of invaders: morphology, coloration and genetics demonstrate that Lysmata rauli is not a new species endemic to Brazil but a junior synonym of the Indo-Pacific L. vittata. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 33 (1), 66 - 77. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 1937240 X- 00002122" type="journal article" year="2013">
Soledade 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Aguilar, R. &amp; Prakash, S. &amp; Ogburn, M. B. &amp; Lohan, K. M. P. &amp; MacDonald III, K. S. &amp; Driskell, A. C. &amp; Ahyong, S. T. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; McIlroy, S. E. &amp; Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A." box="[259,479,1627,1653]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="1" refId="ref16244" refString="Aguilar, R., Prakash, S., Ogburn, M. B., Lohan, K. M. P., MacDonald III, K. S., Driskell, A. C., Ahyong, S. T., Leray, M., McIlroy, S. E., Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A. (2022) Unresolved taxonomy can confounds invasive species identification: the Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (Decapoda: Caridea: Lysmatidae) species complex and recent introduction of Lysmata vittata sensu stricto in the western Atlantic. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 42 (1). https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jcbiol / ruab 079" type="journal article" year="2022">
Aguilar 
<emphasis box="[353,410,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, coloration patterns are an important and powerful character in distinguishing 
<taxonomicName box="[256,440,1663,1689]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis box="[256,350,1663,1688]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Lysmata</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(Rhyne &amp; Lin 2006; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rhyne, A. L. &amp; Calado, R. &amp; Santos, A." box="[691,900,1663,1689]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="71 - 79" refId="ref22637" refString="Rhyne, A. L., Calado, R. &amp; Santos, A. (2012) Lysmata jundalini, a new peppermint shrimp (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae) from the Western Atlantic. Zootaxa, 3579 (1), 71 - 79. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3579.1.4" type="journal article" year="2012">
Rhyne 
<emphasis box="[773,831,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Baeza, J. A. &amp; Behringer, D. C." box="[912,1201,1663,1689]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="3786" refId="ref17337" refString="Baeza, J. A. &amp; Behringer, D. C. (2017) Integrative taxonomy of the ornamental &quot; peppermint &quot; shrimp public market and population genetics of Lysmata boggessi, the most heavily traded species worldwide. PeerJ, 5, e 3786. https: // doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 3786" type="journal article" year="2017">Baeza &amp; Behringer 2017</bibRefCitation>
), particularly among species that are visually similar, such as between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aqua Store, FL" baseAuthorityName="Gordon" baseAuthorityYear="1935" box="[713,853,1699,1725]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grabhami">
<emphasis box="[713,853,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. grabhami</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aqua Store, FL" baseAuthorityName="De Man" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[909,1080,1699,1725]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amboinensis">
<emphasis box="[909,1080,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. amboinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see fig. 
<quantity box="[1187,1231,1699,1725]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Baeza, J. A." box="[1239,1375,1699,1725]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="254 - 265" refId="ref17059" refString="Baeza, J. A. (2010) Molecular systematics of peppermint and cleaner shrimps: phylogeny and taxonomy of the genera Lysmata and Exhippolysmata (Crustacea: Caridea: Hippolytidae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 160 (2), 254 - 265. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2009.00605. x" type="journal article" year="2010">Baeza 2010</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kingsley" baseAuthorityYear="1878" box="[151,302,1735,1761]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[151,302,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rhyne et al. 2012)" baseAuthorityName="Rhyne" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[356,711,1735,1761]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jundalini">
<emphasis box="[356,486,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. jundalini</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rhyne, A. L. &amp; Calado, R. &amp; Santos, A." box="[501,703,1735,1761]" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" pagination="71 - 79" refId="ref22637" refString="Rhyne, A. L., Calado, R. &amp; Santos, A. (2012) Lysmata jundalini, a new peppermint shrimp (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae) from the Western Atlantic. Zootaxa, 3579 (1), 71 - 79. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3579.1.4" type="journal article" year="2012">
Rhyne 
<emphasis box="[583,639,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
or morphologically similar species (Rhyne &amp; Lin 2006). For example, the cleaner shrimp 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aqua Store, FL" baseAuthorityName="De Man" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[443,612,1771,1797]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amboinensis">
<emphasis box="[443,612,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. amboinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1098,1198,1771,1796]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1098,1198,1771,1796]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to a superficially similar morphologies (from preserved material) but displays an unmistakable live coloration pattern compared to any entity in the wider 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[413,515,1843,1868]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[413,515,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[721,877,1843,1869]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis box="[721,877,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">Lysmata rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1257,1359,1843,1868]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1257,1359,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="202">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of dark transverse bands at the first and between the third and fourth pleonal segments, further supporting the resurrection of 
